This tendency of Latin to shorten the final syllable is a decisive argument against those who hold that e. g. senex dari should be pronounced s'neae cl⁷ri⁵⁸ rather than εεηέαε αἀνῖ. But the examples quoted below will show that such shortening is by no means confined to the last syllable: and we must remember also that in early times double letters were not written, which accounts for e. g. 806 intell. 666 supell.⁵⁹.
